{"questionId":"9072684","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Silicon-30&nbsp;<span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\"><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"{\\text{(}}{}_{14}^{30}{\\text{Si)}}\">\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>(</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n  <msubsup>\n    <mrow>\n\n    </mrow>\n    <mrow>\n      <mn>14</mn>\n    </mrow>\n    <mrow>\n      <mn>30</mn>\n    </mrow>\n  </msubsup>\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>Si)</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span></span> can be formed from phosphorus-30 <span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\"><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"({}_{15}^{30}{\\text{P)}}\">\n  <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo>\n  <msubsup>\n    <mrow>\n\n    </mrow>\n    <mrow>\n      <mn>15</mn>\n    </mrow>\n    <mrow>\n      <mn>30</mn>\n    </mrow>\n  </msubsup>\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>P)</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span></span> by a process of beta-plus decay.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Sketch the Feynman diagram that represents this reaction. The diagram has been started for you.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/fe38c942530b76863ba0494d7c32e840c6108860.png\"></p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><img src=\"__IMG__/8d1c4e39118579bd0d1db7479e0229b843c4deed.png\"></p>\n<p>correct change of either u to d ✔</p>\n<p>W<sup>+</sup> shown ✔</p>\n<p>correct arrow directions for positron and electron neutrino ✔</p>\n<p><em>Allow ECF from MP2 in ai for MP3</em>.</p>","meta":{"questionId":"9072684","referenceCode":"19M.2.SL.TZ1.a.ii","subjectId":"46-dp-physics-last-assessment-2024","title":"Sketch the Feynman diagram that represents this reaction. The diagram has been started for you.","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"a.ii","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 3]","breadcrumbLabels":["Core","Core","Topic 7: Atomic, nuclear and particle physics","7.3 – The structure of matter","Core","Topic 7: Atomic, nuclear and particle physics"],"memberSec